collaborative research social networks and the diffusion of microfinance siepr siepr stanford institute for economic policy research search the site enter your keywords main links home about siepr research at siepr centers programs projects education at siepr events at siepr people at siepr publications at siepr economics in the news support siepr contact us stay connected stay connected banner home research at siepr research project collaborative research social networks and the diffusion of microfinance title collaborative research social networks and the diffusion of microfinance principal investigator matthew jackson dates february 15 2008 january 31 2010 sponsor national science foundation the proposed study will examine theoretically and empirically how network structure impacts the diffusion of membership in a microfinance organization in a sample of indian villages detailed data on the network structure will be collected from over 5000 households in 50 villages just before a particular microfinance institution mfi starts working in those villages this mfi will then share data with us regarding which members of the village become clients allowing us to dynamically follow the diffusion process through the pre existing social network we will also obtain data on client behavior amount borrowed and repayment rates and will be collecting detailed background information stanford university economics department stanford center for international development public policy program site map economic summit
